lib_jobs.title: Create Alma Patron XML to Add NET ID data to Accounts missing this identifier

comments.body:
Move the title field to the netid field.  Blank out the title field. Do not modify any other data on the person.

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1cJUCTdGqEOMuYOPSb_x6GFkUXRpUKo6DHQi9uzD3ILM/edit#gid=163688218

We could test and see if the importer would accept the minimal XML we need to make this update

```
<user link="string">
  <primary_id>10101101</primary_id>
  <status>ACTIVE</status>
  <user_title></user_title>
  <user_identifiers>
    <user_identifier segment_type="External">
      <id_type>NetID</id_type>
      <value>mynetid</value>
      <note></note>
      <status></status>
    </user_identifier>
  </user_identifiers>
</user>
```
From the input spreadsheet the title_to_netid field can go in as the NetID identifier.

The user demoed their workflow. 

- **Defect**: **1**. The UR metadata appears as a JSON object. Users need only the url from the metadata for the citation. **2.** UR that has Table of Contents or Publisher Information should be skipped; ideally include the url of the printed record in the catalog.
- **Business Impact**: Librarian emphasized that PHD and MSc students spend too much time cleaning the erroneous URL (UR) from their Bibliographic References.

princeton_ansible.title: Adding a role to initialize the ReCEp machines

comments.body: There are 22,208 arks pointing to http://pudl.princeton.edu/*  .  Each of those web pages must be scraped for metadata that can be used to determine what Figgy object it corresponds with.
@cwulfman Scraping the PUDL pages seems like the most exhaustive way to tackle this — but wouldn't looking in the Figgy database or PUDL METS files be easier (and probably faster)?

I don't think either Figgy or the PUDL METS have the necessary metadata -- I may be wrong.
The object URIs look like `http://pudl.princeton.edu/objects/00000017b`.  The final segment (`00000017b`) is sometimes, but not always, a METS OBJID, so that's probably the right place to start -- you're right. Triage is the name of this game.
